tr: touch (a body part) lightly so as to excite the surface nerves and cause uneasiness, laughter, or spasmodic movements

value.def: When you tickle someone, you move your fingers lightly over a sensitive part of their body, often in order to make them laugh.

example.ex: I was tickling him, and he was laughing and giggling.
example.tran: 我在胳肢他，他哈哈哈、咯咯咯地笑个不停。

value.def: If something tickles you or tickles, it causes an irritating feeling by lightly touching a part of your body.

example.ex: ...a yellow hat with a great feather that tickled her ear...
example.tran: 上面有根大羽毛、搞得她耳朵很痒的一顶黄色礼帽

example.ex: A beard doesn't scratch, it just tickles.
example.tran: 下巴上的胡子不刮人，就是叫人痒痒。

value.def: If a fact or a situation tickles you, it amuses you or gives you pleasure.

example.ex: It tickles me to see him riled...
example.tran: 看见他生气我就觉得忍俊不禁。

example.ex: The story was really funny — it tickled me.
example.tran: 那个故事真有趣——笑死我了。

example.ex: They all sounded just as tickled.
example.tran: 他们听起来好像都很愉快。

value.def: If you are tickled pink, you are extremely pleased about something.

example.ex: 'I'm tickled pink,' said Jimmy after his wife gave birth.
example.tran: “我太开心了，”吉米在妻子分娩后说。
